# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chelsea-massachusetts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] In 1853 the country contains 89 telegraph lines that stretched 23,261 miles (37,435 km).
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] When published in 1854, the country had an estimated 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The area of Chelsea was first called **Winnisimmet**, meaning "swamp hill", by the Naumkeag tribe, which had lived there for thousands of years.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Samuel Maverick became the first European to settle permanently in Winnisimmet in 1624.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] His palisaded trading post is considered the first permanent settlement in Boston Harbor.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In 1635, Maverick sold all of Winnisimmet except for his house and farm, to Richard Bellingham.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The community remained part of Boston until it was incorporated in 1739 and named after Chelsea, a neighborhood in London, England.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In 1775, the Battle of Chelsea Creek was fought in the area as the second battle of the American Revolution.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] During the battle, American forces captured the armed schooner *Diana*.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Part of George Washington's army was stationed in Chelsea during the Siege of Boston.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] On 22 February 1841, part of Chelsea became part of the town of Saugus.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] On 19 March 1846, North Chelsea, which includes what are now Revere and Winthrop became a separate town.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] By the middle of the 19th century, Chelsea had evolved into an industrial city and had become an essential center for the construction of wooden sailing ships.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] As steam power became more common, local industry shifted toward factory production.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] New factories made rubber and elastic goods, boots and shoes, stoves, and adhesives.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Many of these factories were located along Boston Harbor.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The Chelsea Naval Hospital was built during this period.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] It was designed in 1836 by Alexander Parris and became a local landmark.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Local historical records state that Nathan Morse, the first Jewish resident of Chelsea, arrived in 1864.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] By 1890, the city had 82 Jewish residents.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] After 1890, Chelsea became a major destination for immigrants from Russia and Eastern Europe, particularly Jewish immigrants.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] By 1910, the Jewish population had grown to 11,225, making up nearly one-third of the city’s population.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] By the 1930s, Chelsea had about 20,000 Jewish residents out of a total population of nearly 46,000.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Because Chelsea covers a small area, it may have had more Jewish residents per square mile than any U.S. city outside New York City.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] On April 12, 1908, nearly half the city was destroyed in the first Great Chelsea Fire.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The fire left 18,000 people, 56 percent of the population, homeless.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Many residents were taken in by those whose homes had survived, while others sought refuge in nearby Revere.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] It took the city approximately two and a half years to rebuild and five years to surpass the scale of its pre-1908 infrastructure.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Following the fire, the city was redesigned with wider streets and better access for emergency vehicles.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] By 1919, Chelsea's population had reached 52,662, with foreign-born residents making up 46 percent of the total.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The transition from a suburb to an industrial city saw the expansion of the local industrial sector, with shipbuilding, lumberyards, metalworks, and paint manufacturers operating along the waterfront.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] However, between 1940 and 1980, the population declined by 38 percent.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Chelsea lost more residents after the 1950s due to the construction of the elevated Northeast Expressway, built to connect the North Shore suburbs to Boston via the Mystic River Bridge (later renamed for Boston Mayor Maurice J.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In 1973, the Second Great Chelsea Fire destroyed 18 city blocks and affected nearly one-fifth of the city.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The fire originated in Chelsea's "rag shop district," an area where streets contained many small businesses dealing in scrap materials and metal goods.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Similar to the city's earlier major fire, the presence of flammable materials in this area contributed to the severity of the blaze.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The fire spread rapidly through nearby areas with a high concentration of wood-frame buildings and closely spaced multi-family housing.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The following decades saw a decline in the city's economic and fiscal health, accompanied by a developing reputation for corruption, crime, and poverty.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Chelsea's bond rating became so poor that it was unable to borrow money, forcing it to rely on state grants to stay afloat.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] By 1991, the city was running an estimated budget deficit of around $9.5 million against an overall budget of $40 million.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In 1991, the Massachusetts state government declined to provide further financial assistance to Chelsea.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In response, then-mayor John "Butchie" Brennan asked the state to step in.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The state passed a law that placed Chelsea under receivership.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Local elected officials no longer had decision-making authority, and a state-appointed official took responsibility for running the city.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] This was the first time since the Great Depression that a city in Massachusetts had been placed under state control.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Governor William Weld appointed James Carlin as the first receiver.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Lewis "Harry" Spence later followed him.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Under their leadership, fourteen of the city’s seventeen department heads were dismissed, and steps were taken to reduce corruption within city offices.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] During the same period, Brennan and two former mayors were convicted of federal crimes.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The receiver appointed Susan Podziba to facilitate the development of a new city charter, This process included public meetings and an 18-member committee tasked with drafting the document.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Voters approved the new city charter in a special election on 21 June 1994.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The new charter eliminated the position of mayor, changing the city's management from a mayor–alderman to a council–manager system, where a city manager is selected by City Council members.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In the summer of 1995, the state returned local governance to Chelsea, The receivership concluded in 1995 after the city's budget deficit was eliminated and its bond rating reached triple-A.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In the early 2000s, Chelsea began a period of urban redevelopment.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Several unused or underused areas were rebuilt as housing and mixed-use neighborhoods.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] One example is the Forbes Site along the Chelsea River, which was redeveloped into Forbes Park, covering about 17 acres (approximately 6.9 hectares), including housing and small commercial spaces.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In 2018, the MBTA Silver Line was upgraded with new bus rapid transit stations, improving public transportation access in Chelsea.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Chelsea covers 2.21 square miles (about 6 square kilometers), making it the smallest city in Massachusetts by land area.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] It sits on a small peninsula in Boston Harbor, with water on three sides.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] To the west, the Island End River separates Chelsea from Everett.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] To the south and east, the Mystic River and Chelsea Creek form the boundary with Boston.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Along the northern edge, Mill Creek marks part of the border with Revere.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Most of the city lies low and close to sea level, but a series of small drumlins, or hills, rise in different areas.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] These hills, which formed long ago when glaciers shaped the landscape, are now known as Admirals Hill, Mount Bellingham, Powderhorn Hill, Mount Washington, and Mill Hill near Mill Creek.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] This sloped and hilly landscape helps to divide the city into discernible neighborhoods.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] As of the 2020 census, Chelsea had a population of 40,787.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] 23.9% of residents were under the age of 18 and 10.2% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] For every 100 females there were 99.8 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 97.9 males age 18 and over.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] There were 13,795 households in Chelsea, of which 38.9% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Of all households, 33.4% were married-couple households, 23.0% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 34.0% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] About 28.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] There were 14,554 housing units, of which 5.2% were vacant.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.8% and the rental vacancy rate was 4.0%.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] According to the 2010 United States census, there were 35,177 people, 11,888 households, and 7,614 families residing in the city.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The population density was 16,036.8 inhabitants per square mile (6,191.8/km2), placing it among the highest in population density among U.S. cities.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] There were 12,337 housing units at an average density of 5,639.9 per square mile (2,177.6/km2).
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The racial makeup of the city was 47.8% White, 8.5% Black or African American, 3.1% Asian, 1.1% Native American, 0.09% Pacific Islander, 33.6% from other races, and 5.9% were multiracial.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] There were 11,888 households, out of which 36.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 36.9% were married couples living together, 20.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 36% were non-families.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Of all households, 28.8% were made up of individuals, and 10.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The average household size was 2.87, and the average family size was 3.5.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] For every 100 females, there were 100.9 males.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 99.7 males.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The median income for a household in the city was $30,161, and the median income for a family was $32,130.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Males had a median income of $27,280, versus $26,010 for females.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The per capita income for the city was $14,628.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] About 20.6% of families and 23.3% of the population were below the poverty line, including 28.8% of those under age 18 and 20.9% of those age 65 or over.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In 2020, 46% of Chelsea residents were born outside of the United States.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] This is the highest percentage of foreign-born residents in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Its "Interfaith Alliance" brings members of the Jewish, Christian, and Muslim communities together to promote inclusiveness, diversity, and tolerance.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The 2007 Sanctuary City Resolution aims to support all foreign-born residents.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Chelsea has been identified in several crime analyses as having one of the higher violent crime rates in Massachusetts.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Estimates derived from crime datasets place violent crime levels at roughly 800 to 980 incidents per 100,000 residents, significantly exceeding both state and national averages, particularly in assault- and robbery-related offenses.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] However, homicide levels remain moderate rather than high, with murder rates typically at the national average.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Safety rankings frequently place Chelsea among the less safe municipalities in Massachusetts and within lower safety percentiles nationally, with some analyses indicating the city is safer than only a limited share of comparable U.S. communities.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Within the Greater Boston area, Chelsea is often cited as having higher violent crime rates relative to nearby cities, including Lynn, where violent crime levels are almost two times lower despite the city’s historically negative reputation regarding crime.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Depending on the dataset and reporting year, Chelsea’s violent crime rate has been estimated as fluctuating around three times the national average on a per-capita basis.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Chelsea has eight places on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] As of 1995, the city of Chelsea is run by a city manager and an eleven-member city council.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The current city manager, Fidel Maltez, was elected in 2024.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The council is composed of three councilors-at-large and eight district councilors.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] It is currently led by president Roberto Jimenez-Rivera and vice-president Norieliz DeJesus.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The city of Chelsea is a Democratic stronghold, having voted for every Democratic nominee for President since 1928.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Before 1928, Chelsea, like many municipalities in Massachusetts, was a Republican stronghold.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Chelsea Public Schools has four elementary schools, three middle schools, and one high school, Chelsea High School.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The Chelsea school system has historically been towards the bottom of the state's test score rankings.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] A high percentage of students move in or out over the course of the year, and the dropout rate is high.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In 1988, the school board delegated its authority for control of the school district to Boston University.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In June 2008, the partnership with BU ended, and the schools returned to complete local control.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Chelsea has no private schools remaining, with St.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] In addition, there are two public charter schools, the Excel Academy and Phoenix Charter Academy.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Bunker Hill Community College has a satellite location of their school in Chelsea.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The Route 1 North Expressway is a limited-access highway that cuts the City of Chelsea in half.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The Tobin Bridge, a major regional transportation artery, carries Route 1 from Chelsea across the Mystic River to Charlestown.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Chelsea is served by the Massachusetts Bay Transit Authority's Commuter Rail.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The Commuter Rail provides service from Boston's North Station to the Chelsea station on its Newburyport/Rockport Line.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Some MBTA Bus routes have a link to subway transit systems, including 111, 112, 114, 116, and 104.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Chelsea is served by many MBTA bus routes providing local service to East Boston, Revere, Everett, and other nearby cities, as well as bus rapid transit connections to Logan Airport and downtown Boston via the MBTA's Silver Line.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The Silver Line's SL3 route to Chelsea has been in operation since 2018.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The new SL3 route begins at South Station and runs through the Waterfront Tunnel, along with the SL1 and SL2 routes, to Silver Line Way, continuing with the SL1 through the Ted Williams Tunnel.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The new route diverges to meet the Blue Line at Airport Station, and follows the Coughlin Bypass Road (a half-mile commercial-use-only road that opened in 2012) to the Chelsea Street Bridge.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The Silver Line stops at the four stations in Chelsea: Eastern Avenue, Box District, Downtown Chelsea, and Mystic Mall.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] A new $20 million Chelsea commuter rail station and "transit hub" was constructed at the Mystic Mall terminus of the new Silver Line route, so that trains no longer block Sixth Street.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The new Silver Line and commuter rail stations are fully handicapped accessible.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Additionally, a multi-use 0.75-mile (1.21 km) shared path 0.75-mile (1.21 km) linear park runs parallel to the Silver Line bus rapid transit busway, utilizing the Boston & Albany Railroad's Grand Junction Branch right-of-way.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Located within the Box District neighborhood, the path connects the Downtown Chelsea and Eastern Avenue stations.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The Chelsea Fire Department operates from three fire stations across the city.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The fire department operates a fleet of four engines, two ladders, two special operations units, a maintenance unit, a foam-tender unit, and several other special, support, and reserve units.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] They respond to ~11,000 emergency calls annually.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] The Chief of the Department is John Quatieri, who was sworn in on March 8, 2024.
[src:chelsea-massachusetts/chelsea-massachusetts] Emergency Medical Services are contracted to private ambulance provider Cataldo Ambulance Service, which has serviced the city since 1982.
